review_blob: Pours golden and clear as day with a finger head. Aroma is so fresh, like freshly peeled tangerine skin. Citra backs that right up with some dankness and a little bit of malt sweetness. Taste is so fresh, perfect balance between hops malt and fruit. So much tangerine and citrus. Medium mouthfeel with good carb. Overall: my first new Belgium and Im super impressed. Cant wait to try more.

Pours jet black with a slight red tint of a head. Aroma of heavy raspberry and bourbon. Almost smells like a raspberry yoghurt. Taste is quite tart, raspberry, vanilla, bourbon and cream. Thick mouthfeel and nice long finish. Super beer.

Appearance: Pale gold with a finger head. 
Aroma: Wow, heavy tropical fruits. Citrus, orange, grapefruit, mango, pine, plum. 
Taste: Orange, tangerine, grapefruit, mango, pine, hop resin.
Palate: Medium body and carbonation.
Overall: Yes. This is such a juicy and easy drinking IIPA. Honestly wouldnt know it was 8 plus % unless I read the can. Beavertown hit the nail on the head with this one.

Apperance: Pitch dark with a finger tan head.
Aroma: Coffee is very present, but not overbearing, subtle and rounded. Dark malts and a bitter nod.
Taste: Tastes like a straight up flat white. No joke. So smoothe, so subtle, everything is in balance. A little bit of alcohol to let you know your actually drinking a beer. Palate: Thick mouthfeel with soft carb, perfect for this beer. Overall: Amazing beer, this is so balanced & I love balanced beers.

Appearance: Hazy gold with little to no head.
Aroma: lime, citrus, lime, lime and lime. 
Taste: Lime, citrus, very slight tartness, salt, wheat.
Palate: Good carbonation, medium mouthfeel.
Overall. Aroma and taste are so deceiving. Aroma prepares you for an onslaught of lime and taste falls flat. No yuzu detected and little to no tartness or sourness, weakest gose Ive tasted and weakest beavertown too.

Appearance: Straw colour with 2 finger head.
Aroma: Banana, clove, sweet candi sugar and alcohol
Taste: Clove, earthy, dry, alcohol.
Overall: The triple that started it all, great beer that could do with a little age to remove the ethyl acetate left over from fermentation.

Appearances: Pours pale gold with a finger of head.

Aroma: Smells like a bag of citra hops. Tangerine, blood orange, mandarin, citrus and sweet malt. Mouth watering.

Taste: Much the aroma, a burst of citrus in the mouth, lots of oranges with sweet malt to back it up. Bitterness is well presented but not overbearing. 

Palate: Ok, could do with a bit more carbonation, especially for the style.

Overall: One of the better Irish IPAs out there. Finally were starting to see new irish breweries push through the barrier of shitty malty IPAs that so many where getting away with for a long time.

Appearance: hazy orange with a frothy white head

Aroma: a lot of citrus fruit. Grapefruit, mandarins and mango all come to mind. 

Taste: loads more citrus on the flavour, same fruits as the aroma with a hint of lemon in the bitterness and a very subtle malt finish. 

Palate: medium carbonation sits well with this beer.

Overall: for its availability and price, this is a great go yo IPA that still stands the test of time with new breweries emerging.
Actually had on fraught. Lovely head and black body. Aroma heavy roasted with cream. More cream and roast malt. Bitterness in the finish. Classic, but a bit too much bitter in stout for me.

Appearance: dark ruby, more like a IIPA than an imperial red. 
Aroma: citrus out the Ying yang with some sweet caramel malt backing it up. 
Taste: sweet malt and a citrus bang from the hops.
Overall: really nice imperial red, although not so much red in appearance and flavour. Otherwise, such an easy drinking IIPA.
UPDATED: MAR 26, 2016

Appearance: no head, hazy ruby colour. 
Aroma: cherries, raspberries, blackcurrant, gueze, acidic. 
Taste: more cherries and raspberries, quite sour, good tartness. 
Palate: medium bodied, good carbonation.
Overall: expensive, but really nice. Very good sourness and the fruit is pronounced really well. Each sip leave me salivating and begging for another.

Appearance: clear Ruby colour.
Aroma: sweet, caramel, wine, cherry.
Taste: Sweet, toffee, earthy hops, booze.
Palate: good carbonation, medium body.
Overall: nice beer, nothing amazing, but easily drinkable at 9%

Pours golden with a finger of head. Lots of mango, grapefruit and dankness in the aroma. Tastes of mango, sweet caramel, sticky hop resin and sharp bitterness as it exits the palate. Nice session IPA with pure emphasis on the simcoe, which I like, because its a fantastic hop.

Pours jet black with a finger of head. Aroma of cocoa, coffee and super roasted and toasted malts. The smoke is clearly there, but not overwhelming. Tastes of dark bitter chocolate, burnt roasted malts and ash. Reminds me of barrel ages Islay stouts. At 11% this is impressive, very approachable and dangerously drinkable.

Pours pitch black with a finger head. Aroma is of roast malt, wood and milk chocolate. Taste of roast malt, chocolate and noble hops in the finish, A well put together, yet simplistic stout. Drinks VERY easy. Would love to try this on nitro,

Pours deep golden with a one finger head. Aroma of intense pineapple, mango and pine. As it warms sweetness and booze take over. Tastes of sweet caramel malt, candied orange and pine. As 8 degrees warms above 8 degrees, its flaws become apparent. The nose becomes overwhelmed with sweetness and booze. The taste follows the same path, sweetness and alcohol burn begin to take over. Hops dissipate altogether as it warms. This beer walks a very fine line between an okay IIPA and a boozy mess. Fresh out of the fridge it is ok, as it warms, things get messy.

Pours dark orange with a finger of head. Lovely aroma of just straight up grapefruit. Simcoe is sticking through letting you know there are some hops in there too. First thing on the palate is more grapefruit, then comes the hops with the bitterness right behind it, and then finishes again with more grapefruit, and some malt right at the end. Never had a grapefruit IPA before, but this was great, really refreshing. Going to be threat for summer.

Pours mahogany with zero head. Aroma lots of roasty coffee on the nose, Belgian yeast and some sweetness. Medium to thick mouth feel, light carbonation. Smooth taste of sweet classic quad followed by a watered down coffee flavour. This an easy drinking quad with a nice twist. But as far as this fits into the "abstrakt" series, disappointing and not worth the $$$.

Pours murky brown. Aroma is so bourbon forward. Sweet Candi sugar melds with the bourbon to give off a chocolate vanilla smell. Taste of chocolate ice cream, super sweet that is balanced with a bitterness and dry fizzy finish. Really nice brew.
beer_name: Mikkeller Monks Brew (Barrel Aged Bourbon Edition)

review_blob: Pours copper colour with frothy 2 finger head. Lovely aroma of cooking apples, dates, slight spice and a little sweetness from the malt. Taste of deep luscious stone fruit, cinnamon apples followed by subtle hop bitterness and a malty sweet finish. Medium body with good carbonation. Beautiful beer.

Pours gold, with a thick white 2 finger head. Aroma has a lot of pine present. As it warms a little citrus and grapefruit comes through followed by a caramel sweetness. Good carbonation. More pine in the taste with a heavy bitterness, balanced by a malt/caramel sweetness. A good American IPA. Not too extreme on the bitterness, which I like.

Pours a gold with haze. Nice frothy one finger head that stays. The aroma is dank at first, but as you dig in, it opens up into citrus and grapefruit. Taste is sweet, caramel malt, paired well with a burst of juicy and bitter hops all at the one time. A chewy caramel and bitterness lingers in the finish. Overall, really easy to drink IIPA.

Pours amber with 2 finger head. Aroma is very brett forward. Fresh lemon grass, green apples and a twang of funk. Medium carbonation and mouthfeel. Brett is the first thing on the palate, tartness, followed by fresh hops and a subtle bitterness. This is a really nice wild ale, the hops compliment it quite well. Would never think it was 8%

Pours jet black with a finger tan head. Smells great. very fresh, lots of fruity hops, some pine and hop resin and then lots of coffee intertwined with the black malts. Thick mouthfeel, medium carbonation. Loads of fruit up front in the taste, this segue ways into a nice roasted coffee flavour and finishes off with a subtle hop bitterness. I really like what To l have done here, it all comes together very nice as imperial black IPA and its not punishingly bitter as you would expect a IIPA to be.
beer_name: To l Black Malts & Body Salts Black Coffee IIPA

review_blob: Pours jet black with a finger and a half head that dissipates quickly. Aroma gives off some very nice roasty notes, coffee is clearly there along with a heavy oak presence. Some spicy notes in there too followed with some booze. Medium mouthfeel and carbonation. Taste is sweet with a generous helping of roasted malts, chocolate and coffee. Finish lingers with bitterness and woody notes. Complex beer, but all the flavours it advertises are there. Really well executed.
beer_name: BrewDog Black Eyed King Imp Vietnamese Coffee Edition (Can)

review_blob: Pours jet black with a two finger tan head. Smell is so alluring, so much chocolate, peanut butter, bourbon, vanilla. Tastes like vanilla and chocolate ice cream. Slight alcohol burn on the finish. Thick mouthfeel with soft carbonation. By far the best beer I had at the alltech craft beer fest. This is an insanely good beer.

Pours pitch black with a 2 finger tan head. Aroma, straight of the fridge its chocolate on chocolate with roast notes. . As it warms the hops rear their head with cascade shining through. Very smooth mouthfeel, and loads of chocolate and roasted malts in there. It almost tastes like a chocolate stout. Bitter finish. Carbonation is a little too high for this beer. This would be a much better stout without the generous hop additions, they make it unbalanced and draw away from the nice malt bill.

Pours a dark amber red with a finger and a half of tan head. Complex nose. Smells very sweet, caramel, toffee, barrel presence, raisins, cranberries and a hint of smoke. Mouthfeel is medium to thick. Taste, like the aroma, is quite complex. At first it quite sweet, slight caramel and biscuit taste from the malts. A hint of hops, but the taste it primarily dominated by the raisins and whiskey cask. This is defiantly a scotch barrel, because the finish has a subtle peat smokiness to it. A slow alcohol burn on this makes the beer a sipper. 

Really nice beer, so complex and fun to pick apart. Love trying ridiculous beers like this. Tope marks to Brewdog.
beer_name: BrewDog / Ballast Point San Diego Scotch Ale

review_blob: Pours pitch black with two finger tan head. Aroma of roasted malt, coffee, chocolate, grassy hops, and some spice. Creamy mouthfeel. Taste is bitter chocolate, earthy hops, spice. Carbonation compliments this beer. Alcohol burn in the finish. A lot going on in this beer. Im not a huge fan of American imp stouts, but this is done quite well.

Pours jet black with a finger of tan head. Aroma of rich chocolate, coffee, caramel smoke & oak. Taste hits you with the sweetness of the stout, then bam smoke, char and ash from the Islay barrel. Quite intense. As it fades the coffee and roasted dark malts rear their heads and it finishes with some hop bitterness. Thick mouthfeel with medium carbonation. Very nice beer from the beer geek series, had to try because I love Islay whiskeys, and it does not disappoint.
beer_name: Mikkeller Beer Geek Brunch Weasel (Islay Edition)

review_blob:
Pours like a shaken bottle bomb. Gushed all over the place and then gushed out of the glass. This shouldnt happen. Appereance is jet black with a 4 inch head and a stained desk. 

Aroma of roasted malts, bitter hops, plastic, chocolate. Not really getting any barrel character here at all. Maybe some tequila, but its very faint. As it warms, I get a little bit of wine barrel.

Chocolate dominates the taste, little bit of coffee in there too. Not much else. The mouthfeel is so carbonated its hard to dig in to this, its prickly on the tongue and drys away faster than it should. 

Bang for buck ratio, this is possibly the worst mikkeller beer ive purchased. I had high hopes, and wanted it to be good to make up for it gushing all over my desk. Avoid this and stick to their single barrel releases.
beer_name: Mikkeller Beer Geek Breakfast Brunch Big Blend

review_blob: Quite a nice aroma of port, sherry, red wine, stone fruits. Dark as night with no head. Taste starts malty and sweet, develops to some caramel and then BOOM, burnt paper, char, ash, smoke, accompanied by a huge bitterness. The finish on this beer is brutal and punishing. Nice to say ive tried it, but its just too much.

Pours clear golden amber with a long lasting head. Has that unique Lagunitas aroma. Sweet malt. Lots of earthy, spicy hop aromas. Really nice refreshing, crisp, clean taste. Really prominent malt backbone, hoppy taste, and a nice bitter finish with a little alcohol at the end. Great balance. This drink really comes together and Lagunitas shows us that it really knows how to put a DIPA together without going overboard on hops, sweetness or ABV.

Pours jet black with a nice tan head. Super toasty nose. chocolate cake, bitter chocolate, slight hint of booze. Burnt malt, roast malt, smoked malt...so much malt. As it warms some cocoa come through, strong bitter chocolate finish. Thick mouthfeel. Would mark it a lil b(it) higher if it wasnt as bitter as it is, but its still a really nice beer.

Pours with a huge three finger head. Nose is super funky, like James Brown funky. Damp blanket, hay, dry cider. This is a real farmhouse wild ale nose. But i dont know if Im a fan, its so funky and strong it doest allure me to drink it. Taste is of tart apples, cider, Belgian yeast, bready malt and a very subtle sour finish. I find most sours quite quaffable, but this is by no means one of those. Solid carbonation that works well with this beer. A slow burner that actually grows and develops on you as you sip away. Cool if you want to know what sporadic fermentation tastes like in NZ.
beer_name: Tuatara Act of God Sour Abbey Ale

review_blob: Pours jet black with a tan head. Very roasty on the nose, dark chocolate, licorices, a bit of smoke (from the chillies maybe?). As it warms you pick up the rum barrel along with dark berries and stone fruits. Believe it or not, but as soon as it hits my palate, my tongue tingles from the spice of the chillies. Then comes a lot of dark chocolate, finishing with a lingering bitterness. As I sit here my lips are tingling. Reminds me of a chocolate chili con carne. At first I wasnt overly impressed, but as it warmed it revealed itself to be a really interesting beer. Another solid one from To Ol.
beer_name: To l Liquid Confidential (Confidence Rhum Barrel Aged)

review_blob: Pours clear dark ruby with a half finger head. Wow, what a nose. First, your met with a tonne of oak, you can almost smell the charring of the barrels...or maybe you can? So much bourbon, but not overpowering. This plays so well with this wee heavy that we get a beautiful sweet caramel butterscotch nose. Taste is even better. The bitterness balances this super sweet beer and keeps it grounded. Oak, bourbon, caramel, toffee. So good. Make no mistake, this is a sipper. As far as Founders go, this is my favourite Ive tasted from them, even better than KBS in my opinion. A must for barrel aged fans.

Pours dark orange with one finder of head. Aroma is a burst of hops with malt sweetness. Grapefruit, kiwi and mango. The simcoe is strong with this one. Tastes of a lot of bitterness up front, that segways into a nice fruit punch. The caramel sweetness of the malt really helps balance the bitterness into fruit flavours. A tasty bitter bomb just went off i my mouth, but its was thoroughly enjoyable. Galway Bays best beer by far.
beer_name: Galway Bay Of Foam and Fury

review_blob: Having a 2012 vintage. Pours pitch black with virtually no head whatsoever. A heavy smell of chocolate, then comes the toffee, caramel and vanilla. Dig a little deeper and you can unravel the bourbon and oak. Tastes of so much chocolate with caramel and vanilla. The oak is present along with bourbon but it blends so well with the stout. Finishes with a slight alcohol burn & bitterness. Thick Mouthfeel. This is a great beer. With its ABV it begs to be sipped and rightfully so, because it will help you unravel this complex monster.

Pours dark mahogany brown. 1 finger head. Lovely dark fruits on the nose, plums, sour cherry, candied sugar, figs & spice. Tastes of dark fruits, spice, malt sweetness along with some alcohol burn on the finish. Carbonation really helps express the flavours. This beer is what it is, and its really beautiful. If the alcohol burn was less on this beer it would score a lot higher, but at 11.3% what can you do?

Pours pitch black with a finger tan head. Typical imperial stout appearance. Quite a floral nose, more hops than I was expecting from this style. The mixture of hops and malts gives off an interesting bitter dark chocolate nose. First thing I notice is that the taste is bittersweet, the bitterness dominates the sweetness. A lot of wheat comes through to back up this bitterness. Not too sure if I if I like it or not, but its well executed. Tastes of a dark, strong espresso, chocolate and a sharp twang from the wheat. Finish is dry and very bitter. Soft carbonation. Overall, this is an interesting imperial stout, i like how the wheat and hops play together in the taste. But I dont know if id reach for another one again if we crossed paths, too much bitterness for my liking in this style. But a hop lovers dream in stout form.

A lot of floatys in this one, could be the hops (from a massive dry hop addition) could be the yeast, who knows, do I care? Nope. Really nice rounded nose on this. Im getting orange and grapefruit on the nose with some sweetness, smells quite balanced for 13% abv beer. Very Citrusy. Mouthfeel is very thick on this, almost instantly sticky on the lips. Here we go. First sip is a smash of hops, which quickly dissipates to an absolute malt bomb of sweetness and some alcohol burn. Not enough bitterness to balance this immense sweetness. In fairness to the beer, ive drank it two weeks past its best before. A triple IPA really should be enjoyed as fresh as possible otherwise we get a malt bomb of sweetness like so. Id avoid out of date bottles of these. They do not age well. Fresh? This would be amazing.
beer_name: Evil Twin Molotov Cocktail Single Simcoe Hop Edition

review_blob: Pours pitch black with a two finger dark tan head. Smells really roasty, dark espresso. dark chocolate, caramel and toffee. Tastes of dark bitter chocolate & coffee, slight smokiness and a lot more bitter than I was expecting. Medium to full bodied. This beer tastes like a chocolate coffee porter. Better than most beers that actually try to taste like chocolate and coffee. Really nice, but a tad bit on the bitter side for me in terms of a porter.

Pours quite pale with a large head. ALOT of of lemon and lime on the nose. Mouthfeel is quite light, a little too light, watery even. Carbonation is trying to make it feel bigger but its just not working. Taste is of lemon and lime again with a bready malt finish. The taste and mouthfeel is so light it reminds me of washing up liquid water. I think the ABV has a lot to do with this. 3.4% may be just too low for this style.

Pours very pale. straw colour. Lovely refreshing nose on this. Instantly get oranges and mango. Some funk and spice in there too and some....sugar cane? Medium carbonation. Tastes of lemons, slight tartness and dry finish. Really nice, light refreshing beer.

Very pleasant & soft nose. Bready notes upfront and zesty citrus notes in the background. Slightly spicy. Tastes of yeast, cloves, lemongrass, small amount of citrus and coriander. Dry finish.

Refreshing and very complex.

Lots of roasty notes going on here. Some from the malts but predominately from the coffee. Very Earthy. Some slight dark chocolate notes. Pitch black with a tan head. Roasted brown bread chocolate taste. Medium mouthfeel. Meh, id take or leave this stout. Looks better on paper that it actually tastes.

Dark, cloudy orange appearance. Pours with no head. Sweet yeasty smell from this, along the lines of a hefe. Struggling to get anything from the taste here, no coconut, nothing along the lines of gorse flower. Just sweet and dry so it disappears quite quickly.

Wanted something nice for an after work beer, and was thoroughly disappointed with this one. Dont think ill be returning to this nature series or another experimental series from GB again. 

Now, off to the sink I go.
beer_name: Galway Bay In Bloom: Gorseflower Wit

review_blob: Excellent aroma, apples, oranges & pears. Some light wood in the background. Lovely bright granny smith apples on the palate with some well balanced tartness to go with it. Im a fan. Good carbonation to go with it. Overall, this by far my favourite lambic/sour beer from the Boon Brewery. Well worth a purchase if you see it.
